{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1vuillard_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604562/1945080401/0509.xml":{"full_text":"^{je fftwmng ptaf\nWith Sunday Merning Editlsu.\nTHEODORE W. NOTES, Editor.\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nThe Evening star Newspaper Company.\nMain Office: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office- 110 East 42d St.\nChicago Office. 436 North Michigan Ava.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area.\nEffective October 1. 1044.\nRegular Edition. 4 Sundays. 6 Sundays.\nEvening and Sunday 80c per mo. #1.00 per mo.\nThe Evening Star flOc pet month.\nThe Sunday Star 10c per copy\nNight Final Edition. 4 Sundays. 6 Sundaya\nNight Pinal andSunday $1.00 mo. $1.10 mo.\nNight Pinal Star _ 76c per month.\nRates by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAnywhere in Gnited States.\n1 month. 6 month*. 1 year\nEvening and Sunday..#1.00 #J 00 $12.00\nThe Evening Star- .76 4.QQ 8.00\nThe Sunday Star_ .50 2.60 6.00\nTelephone National 6000\nEntered at the Post Office Washington. D. C.,\nas second-class mail matter\nMember of the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use lor republlcation of all news dispatches\ncredited to it or not otherwise credited in this\npaper and also the local news published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein also are reserved\nA\u20148 SATURDAY, August 4,,1945\nNothing Secret\nPresident Truman\u2019s flat statement\nthat he had \"made no secret agree\nments of any kind\u201d at the Potsdam\nConference will further disappoint\nthose who had thought, apparently\non the basis of sheer wishtulness,\nthat some understanding would be\nreached in regard to Soviet partici\npation in the war against Japan.\nThe President\u2019s statement, of\ncourse, does not necessarily mean\nthat Russia will continue in her\nneutral role. But when his dis\nclaimer of any secret agreement is\nadded to the failure of the Potsdam\ncommunique to shed light on the\nfuture lineup in the Pacific war,\nthere can be no legitimate inference\nthat, words to the contrary, a plan\nof concerted action has been worked\nout among the Big Three. In this\nsituation, instead of building up\nexpectations of assistance which\nmay not be forthcoming, it seems\nclearly desirable that we, with our\nactive Allies, should plan on a war\nto the finish with Japan which can\nbe and will be won with or without\nSoviet military support.\nThe communique issued after the\nPotsdam meeting concluded with\nthe cryptic announcement that dur\ning the conference there were meet\nings between the chiefs of staff of the\nthree governments (Russia, Britain\nand the United States) on \u201cmilitary\nmatters of common interest.\u201d What\nthese matters may have been is left\nto conjecture, but an Associated\nPress dispatch from the cruiser\nAugusta, on which the President is\nreturning to this country, conveys\nthe additional information that\nduring the Berlin conference the\nAmerican and British chiefs of staff\nheld daily .meetings to perfect details\nin the co-ordination of British and\nAmerican forces \u201cin accomplishing\na total defeat of the Japanese mili\ntary and naval forces, the uncondi\ntional surrender of Japan at the\nearliest possible date, and the libera\ntion of Japanese-occupied territory.\u201d\nThese discussions resulted in certain\nproposals which have been approved\nby the President and the Prime\nMinister.\nIt has been announced that Mr.^\nTruman will make a report to the\npeople of this country when he gets\nhome, but it is not likely that he\nwill divulge more as to the nature\nof these decisions which have been\nmade to hasten the total defeat of\nJapan. As is the case with the\npossibility of Russian intervention,\nthe world will learn about them\nwhen the time comes to put them\ninto effect.\nRussia and the Baltic\nThe agreement arrived at by the\nPotsdam Conference concerning the\ndivision of the German province of\nEast Prussia between Poland and\nthe Soviet Union is of much more\nthan local importance. The logical\ninference is Anglo-American acqui\nescence in Russia\u2019s contentions on\nother matters not specifically men\ntioned which will result in virtually\ncomplete Soviet dominance over the\nBaltic Sea. I\nSo far as the East Prussia parti\ntion is concerned. Russia gets prac\ntically the entire sea frontage of the\nprovince, including both the port of\nKoenigsberg, the local metropolis,\nand the mouth of the Niemen River.\nPoland gets only the thinly popu\nlated hinterland. Furthermore, the\n\u201cprovisional\u201d Russian border agreed j\non at Potsdam puts the Russians\nonly about 30 air-miles from Danzig\nat the mouth of the Vistula River.\nHowever, that is a point of minor\nsignificance; because, after acquir\ning all of Eastern Germany to the\nOder and Neisse Rivers and expelling\nmillions of Germans therefrom, no\nPolish government can ever venture\nto take an independent attitude to\nward the Soviet Union. Thus, Po\nland\u2019s new frontage on the Baltic\ncan be considered as under Russian\nremote control.\nRussia\u2019s acquisition of the north\nern portion of East Prussia likewise\nimplies Anglo American acquies\ncence in the Russian contention that\nLithuania is organically part of the\nSoviet Union; otherwise, the trans\nferred area would be sundered from\nSoviet Russia by Lithuanian terri\ntory. And what is true of Lithuania\nlogically applies to the two other\u00ab\nBaltic States, Esthonia and Latvia,\nwhich were declared incorporated\ninto the Soviet Union during the\nperiod of Russo-German accord pre\nceding Hitler\u2019s invasion of Russia in\nthe summer of 1941. Those annexa\ntions have never been recognized as\nvalid by the American Government,\nwhich still maintains technically\nfull diplomatic relations with the\nforme? regimes of the three coun\ntries. now in exile though claiming\ntheir Independence and denouncing\nthe Russian action as illegal. For\nthat matter, Britain has likewise\nhitherto not recognized those Baltic\nannexations to the Soviet Union,\nthough it has suspended diplomatic\nrelations with the exiled regimes\nsince its wartime alliance with Rus\nsia. There is thus every presump\ntion that both Washington and\nLondon will soon end this diplomatic\nanomaly in accordance with Russian\ndesires.\nPrudence Demands It\nThe more extreme criticism of\nthe War Department\u2019s demobiliza\ntion policy\u2014notably that of Senator\nJohnson of Colorado, who would\npromptly reduce the Army to 3,000,\n000 men\u2014seems to be predicated on\nthe assumption that the collapse of\nJapan is imminent and that the\nsimple and logical thing to do,\ntherefore, is to discharge millions of\nsoldiers without further delay.\nIt is possible that the assumption\nis right. It is possible that the Jap\nanese will surrender unconditionally\nin the near future. But a possibility\nand a probability are two entirely\ndifferent things, and in the judg\nment of our top military leadership\n\u2014which up to now has demon\nstrated a great deal of competence\n\u2014prudence demands that our Army\nbe maintained at a strength of just\nunder 7,000,000. This number is\nneeded to permit the swift dispatch\nof about 3,500,000 men to the Pacific\nfor direct action against the enemy.\nSenator Johnson\u2019s figure, if we are\nto believe those whose lifetime job\nand responsibility is to plan strategy\nand run armies, would be woefully\ninadequate, upsetting all programs\nfor an expeditious victory over\nJapan.\nIn this connection, it is worth\nremembering that the bulk of the\nJapanese Army is still in being. Our\nNavy may have all but destroyed\nHirohito\u2019s sea power, and our air\nforces may be searing the home\nislands from end to end, but in\nChina, Manchuria and Japan proper\nthe enemy still has something like j\n4,000,000 troops trained and equipped\nfor instant battle, and since Japa\nnese fanaticism may well continue\nto overrule Japanese reasofl, it is\nfoolhardy in the extreme for any of\nus in America to suppose\u2014as if it\nwere a certainty\u2014that little fight\ning remains to be done before Tokyo\nyields and gives us total victory.\nAccordingly, wholly apart from j\nthe fact that wholesale and indis- j\ncriminate demobilization at this\ntime could undermine troop morale j\nand create chaotic transportation j\nconditions, Secretary Stimson is on\nsound ground when he says that thg\nArmy\u2019s present discharge system is\nessential to plans for all-out offen\nsive operations to defeat Japan as\nfast as possible. This ought not to\nmean, of course, that there can be\nno exceptions. The system should\nbe flexible enough to permit the\nfurloughing or release of manpower\ncritically needed in vital industries, j\nThe Army already has begun to let i\nout men to cope with the railroad\njam, for instance, and if the coal\nsituation is really as serious as some\nofficials insist, the same should be\ndone with a percentage of the\nminers in uniform.\nOtherwise, however, with Japan\n\u2022still to be beaten, the War Depart\nment seems altogether right in\nturning a deaf ear to cries for im\nmediate, grand-scale demobilization.\nAs Senator Thomas of Utah declares,\nthe \u201cgeneral rush to collapse the\narmed services\u2019\u2019 can serve only to\nplease the enemy; \u201cit is high time\nfor the Nation to stop enjoying the\npeace in Europe and to get on with\nthe grim war ahead.\u2019\u2019\nErosion Again\nOf course, there is nothing new\nabout erosion. The top soil of the\nearth has been washing into the\nseven seas for hundreds of hundreds\nof years. Nothing can stop the\n\u2022movement of water downhill, and\nwhere water goes there also will go\ngrains or pounds or tons of sand and\nmud, the quantity depending upon\nthe force of gravity in application.\nYet it is not only gravity that\ntransports fragments of the surface\nof the globe from one place to an\nother. Water has a dynamic of its\nown. It rushes as well as falls, and\nanybody who has traveled along the\nAtlantic Coast between Georgia and\nConnecticut since Saint Swithin\u2019s\nday has had opportunity to witness\nthe whole dramatic business going\non in a much bigger way than usual.\nBut the heavy rains of July were\nnot unprecedented and people cer\ntainly did not need them especially\nin order to find out what muddy\nwater in motion looks like. Some\nwho never before had paused to\nthink of the problem involved, how\never, may have become interested\nin it this summer. An entire hill\nside marching\u2014as several are along\nthe Baltimore and Ohio Railroad\nbetween Washington and Laurel\u2014is\nan intriguing spectacle. If enough\nof them moved, the general contour\nof the planet would be changed.\nMen of science reply that that is\nexactly what is happening. Every\ncontinent is sliding into the uni\nversal ocean. But living generations\nof Americans need not worry about\nan eventual inundation of all the\nland areas under the sun. The pace\nof erosion never was too rapid. Even\nthe mpst disastrous floods, like those\nwhich have occurred in the Ohio\nand the Mississippi Valleys, are rela\ntively inconsequential as viewed\nagainst the background of unlimited\nhistory.\nIt is rather the. balance of nature\nthat merits thinking about. The\nmountains of Abyssinia, for example,\nhave been contributing to the Delta\nof the Nile for perhaps half a mil\nlion years. Yet the mountains have\nnot been destroyed completely.\nNeither has the Delta choked the\nwhole Mediterranean. The steady\nrising of the Italian peninsula may\nbe one result of the shifting of\nweight in Egypt and the discernible\nv\ntilting of Britain may be another.*\nThe point to be mindful of is the\nfact that the earth is more friendly\nto man than hostile. All that it\nasks in return is that man may be\nno more willfully careless and waste\nful than in his haste he must be.\nThe top soil upon which the best\ncrops .depend ought not to be dis\nmissed as lost without regard for\nconsequences. Much of it can be\nsaved by intelligent reforestation,\ncrop variation and control.\nThe Coast Guard\nThe Coast Guard is 155 years old\ntoday, and stronger and more effec\ntive than ever. With its 13,000 offi\ncers, its 159.000 enlisted personnel\n(including 10.000 SPARS) and its\n50$00 temporary reservists, it has\ncarried out one of the most Varied,\nfar-ranging and productive jobs of\nthe war. In peacetime it is an arm\nof the Treasury, charged with the\nresponsibility of maintaining the\nsafety of life at sea and enforcing\nthe maritime laws. But ever since\nPearl Harbor\u2014just as in every past\nstruggle America has had with for\neign enemies\u2014it has been an inte\ngral part of the Regular Navy. In\naddition to its usual duties, includ\nmg tne iceDerg patrol ana tne pro\ntection of seal herds, it has guarded\nour home ports against fire and\nsabotage, sped arms cargoes to the\nbattle fronts, manned landing\nbarges in every important amphibi\nous operation all over the world,\nserved invaluably on troop trans\nports, and done valiant convoy work\nin the submarine-infested seas. In\ncombat all the way from the green\nhell of Guadalcanal to the desolate\nwhite silences of the Arctic, suffer\ning many casualties in its ranks and\nproducing more than a few heroes,\nit has more than lived up to the rich\nand proud traditions it has accumu\nlated since that August 4 in 1790\nwhen it was created as our first\narmed naval force. \u201cSemper Paratus\u201d\nis its motto, and \u201cAlways Ready\u201d it\nis, whether in the thick of battle\nor in the sometimes maddening\nmonotony of its normffi routine.\nWhen very occasionally a football\nteam dispenses with signals and\ntells the opposition where the next\nplay will be aimed, the outcome of\nthe game is a foregone conclusion.\nThe 20th Air Force recently an\nnounced to the Japanese the names\nof the next eleven homeland cities\nto \u201cget the business.\u201d\nThis and That\nBy Charles E. Tracewell\nThree factors, two of them little\nsuspected, make the mildew nuisance\nworse.\nIn addition to unusual humidity, lack\nof air motion and shutting up houses\nto help keep them cool are responsible.\nClosing up a home during the heat\nof day is an old-fashioned practice\nwhich does keep a house a bit cooler,\nand in ordinary summers it is not so\nbad, at that, but it cuts oft any chance\nof air movement. And that is bad in\ndamp weather.\nIf one insists on closing up the home,\na liberal use of electric fans, to keep\nthe air in motion, may be advised.\nMoving air dries.\nBuilding up of mildews and moulds\nis partly due to the lack of the drying\neffect of moving air.\nIn the old Washington summers,\nwhen the famous Southern breeze was\na more or less permanent institution,\nthere was not so much mildew, except\nwhere homes were kept too tightly\nclosed.\nToday we lack that breeze, and so\nthe only thing to do is to keep the\nhouse open. Even this will not do so\nmuch good when there are too many\ntrees and shrubs too close to a house.\nEven our suburbs today are maturing.\nNearby Maryland and Virginia com\nmunities are now from 15 to 50 years\nold. Great trees have grown and\nspread and small plantings of ever\ngreens in situations close to the house\u2014\nwhat the real estate men love to call\nfoundation plantings\u2014have grown \u201call\nover the place.\u201d\nThe old saying was that everybody\ntalks about the weather but nobody\ndoes anything about it. Much the same\nmay be said about evergreen pruning.\nThete is much talk as to how, why\nand when to prune, but it is the usual\npractice to do nothing about it at all.\nGreat trees transpire many hundreds\nof gallons of water a day, taking it in\nduring the heat and dropping it down\nduring the night.\nEvergreens cut off what little air\nmovement there is.\nThis results in mildew getting a foot\nhold not only on leather articles in\nclosets but also on rugs and overstuffed\nfurniture, on books and record album\ncovers. Fortunately, the records them\nselves are not often attacked, but\nsometimes they are.\nCalcium chloride, in 'various sorts of\ncontainers, will help a great deal if\nplaced in the basement. An old bucket,\na wire contraption over it, and the\nchemical placed on a piece of burlap\nover the wire\u2014this is a simple home\nmade device which works as well as the\nfanciest one to be bought.\nBut this has its limitations, especially\nif the basement leaks, as so many of\nthem do in the suburban areas.\nThe only answer is eternal vigilance,\nopen windows and doors and more air\nmovement.\nThe electric fan, placed daily so that\nthe air in rooms where things are in\nclined to mildew will be stirred up, is\none of the best solutions. An electric\nlamp permitted to bum will help dry\nout the air. A lamp turned on in a\ncloset often means the difference be\ntween clean and.mildewed articles.\nRed and green cloth suffer more than\nother book bindings. Various types of\nmaterials used on phonograph record\nalbums are susceptible. The best way\nto combat these is to watch carefully\nfor the first signs of mildew and then\nto wipe it off at once with tissues, rub\nbing lightly.\nIn this way most of the damage and\nmost of the smell can be averted, but\ncare should be taken to do the cleaning\nso that none of the mildew is distrib\nuted to other articles. The tissues used\nshould be taken out of the house and\nburned at once.\nMildews, moulds and \u201cathlete\u2019s foot\u201d\nare all related and form an interest\ning group but one which causes much\ndamage and trouble. Its members are\ndifficult' to get rid of if allowed to go\nunmolested. Here again it is a question\nof the famous ounce of prevention, with\ncareful daily inspection, the use of\nlamps and fans and wide-open windows\nand doors during humid weather. Re\nmoval of trees which are too close to\nhouses and cutting back of dense shrub\nbery will do much to help, i\n\nLetters to The Star\nRepresentatiye of Albania Says\nGreek Claims Are False\nTo the Editor ot The Bter:\nUnder date of July 31, the Associated\nPress reported\u2014and your newspaper\npublished\u2014the news that four Greek\nRepublican leaders had addressed a\ncable to the Big Tliree leaders in Pots\ndam asking them to satisfy Greece\u2019s\nclaims \"ahead of those other countries\nwhich the Greeks accuse of jumping\nfrom the Axis to the Allied band\nwagon.\u201d As such, the Greek leaders\nmention Italy, Bulgaria and Albania.\nAs far as Albania is concerned, I, as\none of her leaders and founder of the\nFree Albania movement in the United\nStates, am bound to state that the\nclaims of the Greek leaders are mislead\ning, false and unfounded.\nTo begin with, putting Albania in the\nsame class with Italy and Bulgaria is\ncant and hypocrisy. Albania was in\nvaded in the most cowardly manner by\nFascist Italy on Good Friday, April 7,\n1939, nearly two years before Mussolini\ndecided to attack Greece.\nAlbania, one of the smallest nations\nin Europe, was the first to resist Axis\naggression by the force of arms, whereas\nAustria and Czechoslovakia had suc\ncumbed some two years before without\na single shot being fired. Albania also\nwas invaded in 1944 by Bulgaria in\nconjunction with the Germans.\nIn view of these unconscionable mod\nern Greek extravaganzas, what validity\nmay be attached to the Greek claims\nper se, especially when the Greek lead\ners have addressed the above appeal to\nthe Big Three in the name of \"fair play\nand Justice?\u201d C. A. CHEKREZI,\nFounder of the Free Albania Organiza\ntion in the United States of America.\nOffers a Collection of Don\u2019t*\nTo the Editor of The 8t\u00bbr:\nFollowing are a few wise \u201cdon\u2019ts\u201d\nwhich you may publish if so inclined:\n(1) Don\u2019t sacrifice controlled liberty\n\u2014that all may enjoy liberty\u2014for license\nwhich produces liberty for none. A ma\nchine ungoverned soon tears to pieces.\nA throttle is necessary for an engine;\nan escapement for a clock.\n(2) Don\u2019t sacrifice our constitutional\nGovernment for any tempting scheme\nby whosoever devised or invented. \u201cAll\nis not gold that glitters\u201d and \u201cIt is\nbetter to endure the ills we have than\nto fly to those we know not of.\u201d A gov\nernment cannot be perfect or better\nthan those who compose it. There is\nnone so good as our American form,\nhonestly administered, \u201cfor the great\nest good of the greatest number.\u201d\n(3) Don\u2019t be a chameleon and change\ncolor to suit surroundings. Franklin\nsaid: \u201cIt is hard for an empty sack\nto stand upright.\u201d\n(4) Don\u2019t be a better Samaritan to\nothers than to one\u2019s self. Silly charity\nis never appreciated and the easy mark\nis always despised.\n(5) Don't be selfish or arbitrary, be\nfair and discriminating. Ignoration is\ndefined as \u201clack of discrimination be\ntween objects of thought.\u201d\n(6) Don\u2019t be unreasonable, the other\nfellow has rights and must also live.\nIf you wish your own rights respected,\nconsider and respect those of others.\n(7) Don't fail to apologize when\nwrong. To admit wrong exhibits\nstrength.\n(8) Don\u2019t be partly true and partly\nuntrue. An alloy is not as good as the\npure metal.\n(9) Don\u2019t sacrifice considerate cour\ntesy for ostentatious politeness. One\nis substance, the other shadow.\nGO) Don\u2019t let your worries and\ntroubles make you forget courtesy. \u201cA\nkind word tumeth away wrath.\u201d\n(11) Don\u2019t let your legs replace your\nhead. Leg work solves no problems,\nwearies and wastes time and causes un\nnecessary labor. Planning with the\nhead produces less action with the legs.\n(12) Be careful not to exchange im\nmorality for lack of all morality. The\nfirst is evil but the latter is Indecent\nand intolerable. dt truly decent in all\nthings, good or bad.\nF. S. KEY-SMITH.\nAn \u201cOld Man\u201d at 38\nTo the Editor of The 8t\u00bbr:\nAs an enlisted man of 38 years hu\nmorously referred to as Baldy and Pop,\nI venture to raise my feeble voice. Three\nyears ago at the age of 35 I was a\nmisfit in basic training, being the sub\nject of ridicule as I progressed steadily\nto the rear of the column on 15-mlle\nhikes. But I didn\u2019t mind too much as I\nknew the Army had to be huge in order\nto lick the Nazis and Japs.\nIn the spring of 1943 I saw a ray of\nhope when the Army released most en\nlisted men over 38 as long as they took\nwar jobs. Hurrah! I figured I would get\nout at 38.\nNow with the Nazis beaten and our\nwarships shelling Japan X'still cannot be\ndischarged. Does somebody hate us old\nguys or what? I have three battle stars,\na year and a half overseas and 67 points.\nEven a veteran of Anzio, Normandy (I\nwas there) and the Ardennes will admit\nI deserve a release.\nThe Army has inducted about 10,000,\n000 men in the lastrflve years. There are\nonly 300,000 of us guys over 38. That\nnumber could be obtained from the age\ngroup 28 to 31 alone if the draft boards\nand the Army wanted to.\nWe are a democratic Nation. Why not\nbe democratic in our draft policy and\nlet some more of our former \u201cessential\u201d\nwar workers have a couple of years of\nmilitary service? J. S.\nTraining Through High School\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nThe discussion, pro and con, as to\nwhether this country should have com\npulsory military training for boys in\npeacetime leads me to suggest a way\nto accomplish this training without los\ning a solid year to get it.\nI think it would work out to the\nsatisfaction of most people if the\ntraining would start at the beginning\nof the lint year in high school and run\nthrough one hour a day for live days and\nall day Saturday. This would amount\nto 13 hours a week and 520 hours for\n40 weeks and 2,080 hours for four\nyears. July and August (62 days)\nwould be spent in National Guard\ncamps where intensive training in all\nbranches of service would be given.\nThis would add up to 11)84 hours for\nthe four years or an over-all total of\n4,060 hours. I believe many of the boys\nwould enjoy this way of training. Far\nthose who had physical handicaps, there\nwould be plenty of clerical work to do.\nR. I. ADDY.\nA Professional Reconverter\nFrom the St. nouls Fo\u00bbt-Di\u00abp\u00bbtch.\nFred Vinson ought to be an authority\non reconversion. There\u2019s no one in\nWashington who has been reconverted\nany oftener.\nThis Changing World\nBy Constantin* Brown\nThe Big Three, just nnianea meeting\nat Potsdam, have issued a detailed\ncommunique, the outstanding fact of\nwhich is an agreement on the parti\ntion of Germany. This sensational par\ntition may be provisional, but as inter\npreted by some diplomatic observers, it\nis probably permanent.\nWhatever may be said for or against\nthis decision, opinion is unanimous that\nthe communique is much more satis\nfactory than the statements issued after\nthe Teheran and Yalta Conferences,\nsince the subjects covered are given a\nRetailed and specific treatment. In\nmany ways, the world now has a\nclearer outline of the Intentions of the\nbig powers concerning Germany.\nBut there remain some questions\ncompletely unanswered by the com\nmunique. One is the possible entrance\nof Russia into the Par Eastern war\u2014\nalthough sophisticated observers hardly\nexpected any statement from the con\nference on this matter. The problem,\nhowever, which every one did expect to\nreceive some airing and on which a\nstatement is long overdue is that of the\nNear and Middle East.\nOne of the mysteries of the Potsdam\ncommunique is that it does not once\nmention the Near and Middle East. This\npressing matter, about which Moscow,\nLondon and Ankara have been arguing\nbehind the scenes for some months,\ncould hardly have been overlooked on\nthe agenda at Potsdam.\n\nAfter all, one of the principal motives\nwhich prompted the demands for hold\ning this meeting was the desire to untan\ngle the complicated dispute concerning\nthe status of the Straits of the Dar\ndanelles, Turkish Thrace and the Tur\nkish provinces of Kars and Ardahan.\nWinston Churchill had this particularly\nin mind when he urged both President\nTruman and Premier Stalin to meet.\nIt is known that Mr. Truman made a\nthorough study of these problems, with\nthe aid of many experts in the State\nand War Departments, before he left\nfor Potsdam. With him went a formi\ndable battery of experts on the Near\nand Middle East. If Mr. Truman had\nnothing to say about these matters fol\nlowing the conference, it could hardly\nbe that he was uninformed.\nAlso, it is assumed that incoming\nPrime Minister Attlee was kept fully\ninformed about any developments con\ncerning that part of the world by Mr.\nChurchill. In the closing days of the\nconference, when Mr. Attlee took Mr.\nChurchill\u2019s place, he was undoubtedly\nwell prepared to deal with this as well\nas other questions.\n\nNor is it possible that Soviet Russia\nfailed to bring up the question, one of\nthe historic problems of Russia, whether\nunder the Czars or under the commis\nsars. Russia today, as for many dec\nades past, wants at least some control\nover the vital Straits of the Dardanelles,\nwhich would provide her with an outlet\nto the Aegean.\nRussia also would like to reward her\npuppet state, Bulgaria, witn some oi\nTurkish Thrace, thus giving Bulgaria a\nseacoast on the Aegean. Finally, Rus\nsia wants the return of the strategic\nprovinces of Kan and Ardahan in\nEastern Turkey, which she ceded to\nTurkey following the World War. These\nprovinces have a great military xvalue\nand could command military access to\na large part of the Near and Middle\nEast.\nThis is where Britain comes into the\npicture\u2014for the British Empire long\nhas considered these areas her sphere\nof influence The triangular interests\nof Turkey, Russia and the British Em\npire, if not solved at the Potsdam Con\nference, will have to be dealt with again\nbefore concern about the Near and\nMiddle East is dissipated.\nThe failure of Potsdam to settle this\nquestion, of course, does not impair the\nprestige gained by the detailed treat\nment of the German problem. But\nWhile most interest has been focused\non this major matter, it is evident that\non still other matters, the Big Three\ncame to no agreements.\n\nOne of these is the trial of war crim\ninals. The wording of the communique\nis reserved and measured and quite\nobviously indicates that the views ex\nchanged were by no means identical and\nthat differences were not harmonized.\nThis comes as no great surprise, since\nJustice Jackson\u2019s recent warning\u2014that\nthe United States would proceed alone\nif the other powers could not finish\npreparations\u2014has been widely noted.\nDifferences on judicial procedure and\non the definition of the term \u201caggres\nsion\" as a basis for war guilt are re\nportedly among the differences which\nhave arisen.\nOne clause in the communique has\nstimulated much speculation. It says\nthat the conference \"examined a pro\nposal by the Soviet government con\ncerning trusteeship territories\" and fol\nlows with an explanation that \u201cit was\ndecided that the disposition of any\nformer Italian territories\u201d should be\nsettled at the peace conference involv\ning Italy.\nIt is believed in some quarters that\nRussia thus sought to put the control of\nItalian territories in North Africa under\nsome form of international commission,\nof which she would like to be a member.\nThus, Russia would have a further\nvoice in Mediterranean questions. Her\nambition to participate in the interna\ntional government of Tangier recently\ndrew attention to her interest in these\nquestions.\n\nIt will probably be a cause for re\njoicing in liberal and labor circles that\nno mention was made of forced labor\nfor the Germans. This question pro\nfoundly disturbed the British at the\nYalta meeting, and it may be that Brit\nish objections either eliminated this\nmuch-advertised Russian demand, or\nforced some compromise, the outlines\nof which are not visible in the commu\nnique.\nThe Political Mill\nBy Gould Lincoln\nSeantor Vandenberg. Republican, of\ni Michigan, has taken the lead in urging\nan industrial peace conference in the\nUnited States. He has done it, however,\nnot as a Republican but as an American\n\u2014just as he played an important part\nin the San Francisco United Nations\nConference for international peace. In\nstead of issuing a pronunciamento as\nchairman of the Republican Conference\nof the Senate, the Michigan Senator\ntook the matter up with Secretary of\nLabor Schwellenbach, Democratic mem\nber of President Truman\u2019s cabinet.\nIndustrial peace in this country is as\nessential to the American people as\ninternational peace\u2014and the threat of\nindustrial warfare hangs like a cloud\nin the sky today, threatening Democrats\nand Republicans alike. There should\nbe no partisan politics at the industrial\npeace table.\nThis does not detract from the value\nand wisdom of the proposal made bv\nMr. Vandenberg. On the contrary, it\nadds to both. Further, the Michigan\nSenator has added materially to a\nlong series of constructive proposals\nwhich he has advanced during his serv\nice in the Senate. However, if he per\nsonally and the Republican party: be\ncause of his prominence in that party,\ngain by this proposal, that is a natural\noutcome, particularly if his proposal is\nadopted and proves a success. It was\nMr. Vandenberg, who last winter in a\nremarkable address to the Senate gave\nimpetus to the demand for a United\nNations Conference for future world\npeace and helped to strip the last shreds\nof isolationism from the Republican\nparty.\n\nThe late President Roosevelt was\nprompt to seize upon a nonpartisan ap\nproach to America\u2019s part in the effort\nfor external peace\u2014an American foreign\npolicy, rather than a Democratic foreign\npolicy. He appointed three Republican\nmembers of the United States dele\ngation to the United Nations Confer\nence, and Senator Vandenberg was\none of them. They all did yeoman\nservice, sinking political partisanship in\nthe interest of a common American\ncause. President Truman, it is expected\nwill be as nonpartisan in his approach\nto an industrial peace conference. He\nshould.\nThis nonpartisahship, in an effort\nto bring order to American industrial\nrelations, has manifested itself in an\nother direction. Two Republican Sen\nators, Bail of Minnesota and Burton\nof Ohio, have joined with Senator Hatch\nof New Mexico, Democrat, in the intro\nduction of a comprehensive bill to estab\nlish a more definite labor policy for the\nFederal Government. All three of these\nSenators were sponsors of a resolution\nlong before Dumbarton Oaks Conference\nwas called, looking to international\npeace.\nIf there should also be a show of\nnonpartisanship among the representa\ntives of labor and management who\nwill be called upon to confer on in\ndustrial peace, there will be a real\nchance of success. Senator Vanden\nberg, in his letter to Secretary Schwel\nlenbach, has put it succinctly. He said:\n\u201cNow that we have laid the ground\nwork for external peace with justice,\nthere remains the necessity to find the\nbasis for peace with justice on the home\nfront. We must create a mutually\nequitable relationship between capital\nand management, on the one hand, and\norganized labor on the other hand\nprotecting the legitimate rights of each,\nand always consulting the general wel\nfare\u2014to the end that needless strife\nhall not impair reconversion and per\nmanently jeopardize the country and all\nits citizenship.\u201d\n\nLeaders of organized labor and of\nmanagement and capital already have\nexpressed their approval of the \"United\nIndustrial Peace Conference\u201d suggest\ned by Mr. Vandenberg. It is to the\nvital interests of both that peace be\npreserved, as well as to the interests\nof the entire country. The conference,\nif it is properly constituted and con\nducted by men of good will, can ac\ncomplish a tremendous amount of good.\nIf \u201cpeace with justice\u201d can be had on\nthe industrial front a great stride will\nhave been made.\nSenator Vandenberg put his finger on\nthe essential when he asked: \"Is it not\npossible that such a conference could\nescape- from intrenched rivalries long\nenough to deal fundamentally with the\nequities which are prerequisite to the\nhealthy pursuit of better times for all\u2014\nand for all America?\u201d The answer must\ncome from the conference itself.\nWhat Price Automobiles\n\u2019By Raymond Moley\nThe pathetic struggles of the OPA\nover the fixing of prices on forthcom\ning new automobiles suggest how much\neasier it is to get government into pri\nvate business than to get it out. The\ncar-pricing example illustrates the pains\nthat are ahead in months to come with\nmany other kinds of business.\nIt has been announced that the ceil\ning has been fixed for Wlllys-Overland\njeeps. But these cars have been in war\nproduction, and the revised model is\nnew to the civilian market.\nThe OPA has approached the task .of\nfixing the prices on models discontinued\nduring the war with the boldness and\nconfidence of a wren trying to steal\nfood from a kingfisher. Questionnaires\nwent out on which manufacturers of\nparts labored for periods as long as\nsix weeks. Conference dates with the\nlarge manufacturers were set and then\npostponed. A meeting in Washington\nwas held, and the manufacturers found\nthat the OPA experts were able to speak\nonly in lofty generalities.\n\nThen \u201ctask forces\u201d of Washington\nfunctionaries appeared in Detroit and\nsat down with manufacturers\u2019 account\nants. These labors went on and on.\nNow the \u2018\u2018task forces\u201d have returned\nto their base in Washington.\nThe reasons for the difficulties in\nfixing prices on the new cars are not\nhard to see. Some producers of the\nmany parts which go into automobiles\nhave gone ipto other lines of manufac\nturing. Other manufacturers of parts\ndon\u2019t know whether they will make\nthe same products again. All their basic\nelements of cost have changed\u2014wages,\ntransportation and materials.\nIn most cases, manufacturers, both\nof finished cars and of parte, must move\ninto civilian production gradually. War\ncontracts involve profits. Civilian pro\nduction will involve initial losses. The\njob of balancing war profits and civilian\nlosses in a given year is practically an\nimpossible one, since the rate of tran\nsition is not uniform as among com\npanies and can hardly be predicted.\n\nIf the OPA sets prices applicable to\nthe industry as a whole, weaker com\npanies will be badly squeezed. If each\ncompany is dealt with separately, the\npublic will be subsidizing the weak ones.\nIf ceilings are set by models, some manu\nfacturers point out that nothing will be\nthe same but the name. One manufac\nturer was asked if he would accept the\n1942 price on Model X. \u201cWhat Model\nX?\u201d he answered. \u201cWe will not be\nmaking that model again. There will\nbe a hundred changes.\u201d\nIf the OPA sets prices on finished\ncars and lets parts prices go natural,\nthe car manufacturers, who are fierce\ncompetitors and tough buyers, will hold\nprices down themselves. Such a policy\nmight work in the automobile industry,\nbut it probably would not work in many\nothers.\nIf the Government should decide that\nautomobile price fixing is too hard to\nwork out and decides on no controls,\nthere will be demands for similar treat\nment by hundreds of other industries.\nFinally, if delay and hesitation are the\nrule, civilians will be denied their needs,\nand unemployment will pile up.\nThis complex situation faced by the\nOPA is only one side of a larger situa\ntion with many, many more sides. Prec\nedents set here will apply to hundreds\nof other articles. And no one knows\nbetter than the OPA how difficult it is\nto set precedents and to hold them.\nWhen we bring government into busi\nness, we weave a tangled web.\n(XtleiMd br Tht Associated Newspaper* hie.)\nWar Department Seen\nTaking ItoatheChin'\nJaps Fishing for News on Speed\nOf Troop Moves, Says Writer\nBy David Lawrence\nThe War Department Is taking it on\nthe chin these days for not telling the\npublic just how many troops were to\nbe moved across the continent and why\nwe needed to hurry or why Pullman\ntravel has to be curtailed or why no\narrangements to meet the crisis were\nmade. But any one who reads the latest\nextracts from Tokyo newspapers which\nare broadcast can see that the Japanese\nhave an idea of what has been happen\ning and are trying to find out more.\nPlainly the quantity of troops to be\nmoved and our schedule is something\nthat interests the Japanese very much.\nThe Tokyo radio says \u2018\u2018an American\nlanding operation against Japan may\ncome in the near future\u2014even as early\nas next month.\u201d\nThe Japanese go on to comment that\nthey have observed 500 ships concen\ntrated around Okinawa and they esti\nmate that if the invasion happens this\nyear we can mount only 40 divisions and\nthat our maximum next year would be\n100 divisions \"even if all-out attention\nis given to the transport of men from\nEurope to East Asia.\"\nFishing for Information.\nThe Japanese are Ashing for informa\ntion. They would like to know what\nAmerican divisions were sent from\nEurope and what ones we are sending\nfrom the United States and when they\nwill all be assembled and in what\nnumbers.\nWhen landing operations become im\nminent, the Japanese by reconnaissance\nplanes can observe considerable activity\nbut they cannot tell where the expedi\ntion is going or when it will set sail and\njust when it will strike. There is no\nsecret in the fact that we are concen\ntrating troops in various areas of the\nPaciAc. It is obvious that large quanti\nties of ships are needed to transport the\ntroops and that Okinawa and the Philip\npines are two of our main stations for\ngathering troops. But the Japanese will\nnot know when we intend to invade or\nat what points either in China or Japan.\nThe Germans were kept guessing and\nguessed wrong as to our landings in Nor\nmandy though they had no doubt, from\nobserving preparations on the English\ncoast, that an invasion was coming.\nII the Japanese are right in their\nassumption that we can mount only 40\ndivisions, or about 600,000 men, in any\noperations in 1945, what they are saying\nis that V-E day and the necessity for\ngiving American troops furloughs at\nhome and other changes in our military7\nsetup in connection with the transition\nfrom Europe to the Far East have pre\nvented the assembly of a larger force.\nJust to what extent the demand for\na point system for discharge and the\npressure to demobilize our forces in\nEurope and send them home has delayed\nthe ending of the Japanese war prob\nably will not be known till after V-J\nday. The mothers and fathers of the\nboys who are fighting in the Pacific\nwill some day want to know whether\nthe high command in America let them\ndown by yielding to public pressure\ninstead of insisting on sending our full\ndivisions intact direct to the Far East.\nDelay in Replacements.\nFor the point system has meant that\nArmy divisions that come to the United\nStates have had to be torn apart and\nreplacements found. This means delay,\nbut it is not revealed how extensive the\ndelay has been. It will be noted, how\never, that the War Department has just\npostponed a revision of its plan to\nreduce the number of points necessary\nlor discharges from the Army and it is\nreported that this was due to protests\nfrom Gen. MacArthur and others in\ncommand who do not want to see our\ndivisions delayed in getting reorganized\nand transported to the Far East.\nThe size of the Army for 1945 and\n1946 is another moot question. Members\nof Congress feel it can be reduced con\nsiderably even before Japan is beaten,\nbut the War Department cannot dis\nclose what categories of troops can be\nreleased or the nature of the changes\nin the divisions without telling the\nenemy what our plans will be ;to follow7\nup any invasion landings that may occur\nin 1945.\nOn the whole there is a feeling here\nthat the Japs may be right about the\npossibility of an invasion this year but\ntheir whole plan of defense against it\nmay turn on how much they can find\nout as to the strength of the forces we\nhave available in the Far East or will\nh\u00bbve available at particular moments in\nthe next several months. The War\nDepartment\u2019s necessary silence at this\ntime will be vindicated in the end.\n(Reproduction Rights Reserved.)\nWar Criminals\nFrom the Manchester Guardian.\nMr. Justice Jackson\u2019s report to the\nPresident on the trials of the major war\ncriminals puts forward a strong and\ndefinite policy, which, just because it\nraises many difficulties, should be thor\noughly discussed. He is dealing only\nwith the chief accused, those mainly\nresponsible for \u201ca grand concerted pat\ntern to incite and commit the aggres\nsions and barbarities which have\nshocked the world.\u201d By what law shall\nthey be judged? \u201cThose acts which\noffended the conscience of our people\nwere criminal by standards generally\naccepted in all civilized countries.\u201d\nClearly the appeal here is to that de\nveloping law, the law never written but\ngraven in the hearts of men, the law of\nnature. While the doctrine of the\nnatural law has an hbnorable ancestry,\nthere is always a danger in appealing\nto conscience for legal sanctions, be\ncause consciences are varying things,\nsubject to emotional excitement.\nSight\nSoils\u2019 eyes grow dim, the eyes through\nwhich are seen\nThe things that mortal sight to me*\ndenies,\nUnless their vision be kept sharp and\nkeen\nBy the leaf which does the band\nepitomize,\nBy triUium, vagrant In the wood, the\nblade,\nAnd pine the cloud reclines upon to\nrest,\nBy meadow nests the bobolinks have\nmade\nNear cottonwoods by ffypsy streams\npossessed.\nThese are the things, and others similar.\nWhich are as lens through which may\nbe discerned r\nThe Artist\u2019s Hand that fashioned the\nfirst star,\nAnd from dark nothingness and chaos\nturned\nOut the green earth with bough and\nsong to frame\nThe gracious picture where is signed\nHis name.\nEDWARD D. GARNER.\njf.","height":"31676","width":"22188"}}
